        <DemoExample Title="IQueryable data source" RazorCode="@example27RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example27CsharpCode" Id="example27">
            <div>
                Bind an <code>IQueryable&lt;T&gt;</code> to <code>Items</code> and the grid translates filtering,
                sorting and paging into <b>expression trees</b> composed onto the queryable - so a remote LINQ
                provider such as EF Core executes them at the source (SQL <code>WHERE</code>/<code>ORDER BY</code>/<code>OFFSET</code>)
                and only the current page is ever materialized. This example uses an in-memory queryable;
                bind <code>dbContext.Products</code> the same way.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@queryableProducts" Height="430px"
                         Sortable="true" Filterable="true" Pageable="true" PageSize="10">
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Id" Title="ID" Width="70px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" Filterable="false" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="220px" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Supplier" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Price" Format="C2" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Stock" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Excel export" RazorCode="@example28RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example28CsharpCode" Id="example28">
            <div>
                <code>ShowExcelExport</code> adds a toolbar button that downloads the full (filtered/sorted)
                data as a real <code>.xlsx</code> workbook - generated in-process with no external library.
                Numbers and booleans are written as native cell types so spreadsheet formulas work on them,
                and the workbook mirrors the grid's layout: a bold, frozen header row, the grid's column
                widths, frozen columns as Excel freeze panes and <code>ColSpan</code> cells as merged cells.
                With <code>ExcelExportStyled</code> the workbook also carries the grid's <b>current visual
                theme</b> - the rendered header/row colors, the striped alternating background, the border
                color and bold/italic fonts are sampled from the live DOM at export time, so whatever theme
                is active (light, dark, custom) is what lands in the file.
                Exports always cover <b>all</b> matching rows, not just the rendered ones: server and
                infinite-scrolling modes fetch the full set through <code>OnRead</code>/<code>OnLoadMore</code>,
                and tree mode includes collapsed branches.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@excelProducts" Height="430px"
                         Filterable="true" Pageable="true" PageSize="10" Striped="true"
                         ShowToolbar="true" ShowCsvExport="true" ShowExcelExport="true" ExcelExportStyled="true">
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Id" Title="ID" Width="70px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" Filterable="false" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="220px" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Category" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Price" Format="C2" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Stock" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Discontinued" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Center" />
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Export with complex layouts" RazorCode="@example33RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example33CsharpCode" Id="example33" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
            <div>
                This grid combines a master-detail <code>DetailTemplate</code>, frozen ID/Name columns and
                <code>ColSpan</code> spanning (discontinued rows span Name over Category) - try scrolling,
                expanding details and filtering, then export. The <b>Excel</b> file mirrors the layout:
                the frozen ID/Name columns (plus the header row) become a freeze pane and each spanning
                cell becomes a merged cell. The data stays faithful in both formats: frozen columns keep
                their declared order, a templated field column (Name) exports the raw field value rather
                than its markup, detail content is not exported (master rows only), and the template-only
                Value column (no <code>Field</code>) is skipped. <b>CSV</b> has no layout concepts, so it
                stays flat - there every column exports its own value, including the Category a span covers.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@complexExportProducts" Height="460px" Bordered="true"
                         Sortable="true" Filterable="true"
                         ShowToolbar="true" ShowCsvExport="true" ShowExcelExport="true" ExcelExportStyled="true">
                <DetailTemplate Context="p">
                    <BitStack Horizontal Wrap Gap="2rem">
                        <div><strong>Supplier:</strong> @p.Supplier</div>
                        <div><strong>Rating:</strong> @p.Rating.ToString("N1")</div>
                        <div><strong>Released:</strong> @p.ReleaseDate.ToString("yyyy-MM-dd")</div>
                        <div><strong>Discontinued:</strong> @(p.Discontinued ? "Yes" : "No")</div>
                    </BitStack>
                </DetailTemplate>
                <Columns>
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Id" Title="ID" Width="80px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" Frozen="true" Filterable="false" />
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="220px" Frozen="true" ColSpan="p => NameSpan(p)">
                        <Template Context="p">
                            @if (p.Discontinued)
                            {
                                <span class="span-banner">⚠ @p.Name - discontinued</span>
                            }
                            else
                            {
                                @p.Name
                            }
                        </Template>
                    </BitDataGridColumn>
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Category" Width="170px" />
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Price" Width="150px" Format="C2" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Stock" Width="130px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                    <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Supplier" Width="200px" />
                    <BitDataGridColumn ColumnId="Value" Title="Value" Width="140px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right"
                                       SortBy="@(p => p.Price * p.Stock)">
                        <Template Context="p">@((p.Price * p.Stock).ToString("C0"))</Template>
                    </BitDataGridColumn>
                </Columns>
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Lazy tree loading" RazorCode="@example29RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example29CsharpCode" Id="example29" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
            <div>
                Set <code>ChildrenProvider</code> (instead of <code>ChildrenSelector</code>) to fetch a node's
                children <b>asynchronously on first expand</b> - e.g. from a backend - with the results cached for
                later toggles. Pair it with <code>HasChildrenSelector</code> so unloaded nodes know whether to
                render an expand toggle. Expanding a folder below simulates a 600&nbsp;ms backend call.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@lazyTreeRoots" Height="430px"
                         ChildrenProvider="LoadChildrenAsync" HasChildrenSelector="IsFolder"
                         KeyField="n => n.Id" Sortable="false">
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="280px" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Kind" Width="110px" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Size" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" Format="N0" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Modified" Format="yyyy-MM-dd" />
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Touch drag &amp; drop" RazorCode="@example30RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example30CsharpCode" Id="example30" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
            <div>
                Row and column reordering work with <b>touch and pen</b> as well as mouse: pointer-event based
                drag-and-drop drives the same reorder pipeline on devices where native HTML5 drag-and-drop
                doesn't fire. Try it on a touchscreen - drag the ⠿ handle to move a row, or drag a column
                header to reorder columns; the drop target is highlighted while dragging.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@touchReorderProducts" Height="430px"
                         RowReorderable="true" Reorderable="true" Sortable="false" KeyField="p => p.Id">
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Id" Title="ID" Width="70px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="220px" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Category" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Price" Format="C2" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Column virtualization" RazorCode="@example31RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example31CsharpCode" Id="example31" PreventRenderForMcpClient>
            <div>
                <code>VirtualizeColumns</code> renders only the columns in (and near) the horizontal viewport,
                replacing scrolled-out runs with spacer cells - for grids with very many columns. This example
                declares 40 measurement columns (plus a frozen ID column) but only the visible window exists in
                the DOM while you scroll horizontally. Combine it with row <code>Virtualize</code> for large
                datasets in both dimensions. Columns need explicit pixel widths.
            </div>
            <br />
            <BitDataGrid Items="@wideProducts" Height="430px"
                         VirtualizeColumns="true" Virtualize="true" RowHeight="36" Sortable="false">
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Id" Title="ID" Width="80px" Frozen="true" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right" />
                <BitDataGridColumn Property="p => p.Name" Width="200px" />
                @for (var m = 1; m <= 40; m++)
                {
                    var month = m;
                    <BitDataGridColumn ColumnId="@($"m{month}")" Title="@($"M{month:00}")" Width="110px" Align="BitDataGridColumnAlign.Right">
                        <Template Context="product">@(((product.Id * 37 + month * 13) % 1000))</Template>
                    </BitDataGridColumn>
                }
            </BitDataGrid>
        </DemoExample>

        <DemoExample Title="Programmatic control" RazorCode="@example32RazorCode" CsharpCode="@example32CsharpCode" Id="example32">
            <div>
                Everything a user can do through the UI is also a public API on the grid: drive sorting,
                filtering, grouping, paging and refresh from code with <code>SortByAsync</code> /
                <code>ClearSortsAsync</code>, <code>ApplyFilterAsync</code> / <code>ClearFiltersAsync</code>,
                <code>GroupByAsync</code> / <code>UngroupAsync</code>, <code>GoToPageAsync</code>,
                <code>SetPageSizeAsync</code> and <code>RefreshAsync</code>.
